PRINTF(1)                      User Commands                      PRINTF(1)

NAME
    printf - format and print data

SYNOPSIS
    printf FORMAT [ARGUMENT]...

DESCRIPTION
    Print ARGUMENTs under the control of FORMAT, in the style of the C
    printf function. FORMAT is reused as often as needed to consume all
    ARGUMENTs. Interpreted sequences in FORMAT include:

        \n \t \\ \" \r      the usual C escapes
        \0NNN               a byte with octal value NNN
        \xHH                a byte with hex value HH
        \uHHHH \UHHHHHHHH   a Unicode code point, emitted as UTF-8
        %s %d %i %o %x %c   the usual C conversions, plus %b (escapes in
                            the argument) and %q (shell-quoted)

    This is the unmodified GNU coreutils printf(1), ported to Horus and run
    as a ring-3 program from /bin/printf.

NOTES
    The shell splits a command line on spaces, so quote nothing special is
    needed: `printf %s=%d\n foo 7` prints "foo=7" followed by a newline
    (printf expands the \n itself).

EXIT STATUS
    0 on success, non-zero on a bad format or conversion.

SEE ALSO
    seq(1), echo(1), hier(7)
